Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[In the past 24 hours, the USA (149 446), India (48 285), and Brazil (47 724), have been dominant. A global total of 10 345 deaths were reported in the past 24 hours (10-11 Nov 2020). The global total is now above 52.4 million cases.

Countries reporting more than 10 000 newly confirmed cases in the past 24 hours (13 countries) include the USA, India, Brazil, France (35 879), Italy (32 961), Poland (25 221), UK (22 950), Germany (20 536), Russia (19 851), Spain (19 096), Iran (11 780), Argentina (10 880), and Ukraine (10 611). A total of 58 countries reported more than 1000 cases in the past 24 hours; 32 of the 58 countries reporting more than 1000 newly confirmed cases are from the European region, 9 are from the Americas region, 8 are from the Eastern Mediterranean region, 5 are from the South East Asia region, 2 are from the African region, and 2 are from the Western Pacific region.

Comparing the 7-day averages of daily confirmed cases from the past 7 days and those from 8-14 days ago, case counts have increased by 9.7%, while daily reported deaths have increased by 20.5%. Looking at the same comparisons in the USA (which reported 23.8% of all newly reported cases in the past 24 hours), as the dominant country worldwide with clearly uncontrolled transmission, the 7-day change in daily reported cases is 32.4% and in reported deaths is 9.2%.

Impression: The global daily reported cases continue to increase with the daily increase between 500 000 and 600 000 new cases. Countries in the European and the Americas regions are still showing the largest increases in daily new case counts, followed by the Eastern Mediterranean and the South East Asia regions. Italy may cross the 1 million mark for cumulative cases in the next 24-48 hours, bringing the number of countries reporting more than 1 million cases to 10.

All in all, the growth in the USA is exponential, having surpassed the 10 million cumulative case mark, with the state of Texas having reported over one million cases and California will be crossing one million cases very soon assuming daily reports continue at the same rate. - Mod.UBA]
